snippet.textDisplay:
Comedy-sin-festival aside, this is one of the best directed movies I've ever seen.
So unique, in fact, that when I walked in on a showing of "Baby Driver", having known nothing about Edgar Wright, I immediately knew it was his work within 10 seconds, after having seen this film.

I love the references, the nerd culture, and how amazing the VFX is. It's so relevant and tongue-in-cheek. A literal masterpiece of direction. Comic book IRL - I wish so bad that more films would use Edgar's style. Life as a video game... iconic.

Fun fact: the movie is based off the comic series of the same name: panel-to-shot, Edgar stuck to the material as literally as possible. Look it up; it's fascinating. Every single detail, as close as it could be, was translated from publication to film.

Also in the comics, Scott actually did fight dozens of baddies and punched a guy so hard he saw the curvature of the Earth (via his and Kim's breakup reference).

While I believe I read somewhere that in the comics Scott ends up dating Kim, Knives, Ramona, and Natalie (Envy) at the same time, the original [film] ending had Scott dating Knives over Ramona. Edgar felt guilty about having 3/4 the journey seeing Scott fight for Ramona that the film-ending sees them leave together instead of Knives.

You can see more in the director's commentary of the film.

P.S. The video game adaptation is a delight: side-scrolling mayhem with character specialization and an 8-bit soundtrack by Anamanaguchi that's to die for ("Another Winter" is a song you'll never get out of your head).
